The previously amicable relationship between England and Frisia started to fall apart in the midsts of the two former allies' wishes to influence the increasing amount of trade in the narrow sea. By 1542, England had taken a stance that flared up tensions through the repeated blockading of Frisian ports. The war served as a wake-up call of sorts to Frisia, and obligated it to expand and modernize it's (presumably) previously lacking navy. War officially began with the Battle of Amsterdam. It ended with a surprising Frisian victory against the much larger English Navy.
